<li>In Proposition 1.1.3, add the note that
\(\frac{partial f}{\partial z_k}\) is holomorphic.
(thanks to a suggestion by Richard Lärkäng)
<li>Slightly add to the hint to Exercise 2.1.5.
(thanks to a suggestion by Richard Lärkäng)
<li>In proof of corollary 2.1.5, explicitly mention that
\(H \subset U \setminus \{ p \} \text{,}\)
rather than just \(H \subset U \text{.}\)
<li>Change the hypothesis on the sequence of discs to
converge uniformly in Theorem 2.1.7 to fix an erratum.
Alternatively one could also assume that the boundaries
stay inside some compact set, which would make the proof work,
but that makes the statement too clunky and unwieldy. 
<li>In the discussion on page 56 about why \(X_p f\)
only depends on the values of \(f\) on \(M,\) be a little
bit more precise and avoid writing \(r\) or \(g\) when we
mean \(r\) or \(g\) evaluated at \(p.\)
<li>Reword the proof of Theorem 2.3.11 a little to choose
the \(s\) correctly to fix an erratum reported by
Richard Lärkäng.
<li>In the proof of Theorem 2.4.10, when integrating in 
polar coordinates, don't
integrate over the epsilon polydisc to avoid confusing abuse of notation.
We had better integrate over the ball, and that's not actually hard.
Otherwise after applying Fubini we may be integrating f outside its 
set of definition, which is not really a problem as we are multiplying
that by zero, but it is unnecessary abuse.
<li>In Exercise 2.6.17, add a note about convention handling
\(\alpha_j=0.\)
<li>In proof of Theorem 2.6.3, choose \(f_1\) so that \(|f_1(p_1)| \geq 1\)
(that is add in the absolute values).  There is no reason to make \(f_1\)
real at \(p_1\) and it may be confusing.
<li>Add a note in 6.5 about (sub)varieties in algebraic
geometry often being defined to be irreducible.
(thanks to a suggestion by Richard Lärkäng)


